<br />

<h2 class="pen"></h2>

<div class="post">

<div class="entrytext">

	<p>I actually did something constructive last night. I started filling in the million nail holes and cracks left on the plaster walls over the past 150 years. It was actually kind of fun as scary as I find that.</p>

	<p>My friend Pat the tinman is a strict preservationist and he&#8217;d kill me for scraping off the old wallpaper that&#8217;s underneath. He&#8217;d prefer I uncovered as much as I could so he could reproduce it and put it back up. His friend is a printmaker and they could pull it off. Mind you he&#8217;s been working on doing that with his house for a few years now, but is still working to redo the plaster.</p>

	<p>Well, I&#8217;m only doing a quarter of the room to start. We&#8217;ll experiment with paint colors on that before doing the whole room. Thus there will still be 3/4 of the room for him to play with.</p>

	<p>I did manage to peel the paint off one of the wallpapers. It is a flower motif made out of red and white dots- a tacky impressionistic feel. Below that is a blue and gold wallpaper, though I haven&#8217;t uncovered enough of that to figure out what it looks like.</p>

	<p>No, the wallpaper isn&#8217;t worth preserving. Pat believes they knew how do design back in the Victorian days. You just had to see everything and not judge it from one piece of wallpaper.</p>

	<p>Some of it I don&#8217;t mind. I could easily live in the house from &#8220;My Fair Lady&#8221; and I love old places, but I&#8217;ll stick with my own interior colors thank you very much.</p>

	<p>We&#8217;re thinking of an a dark avacado with some sort of off white trim and ceiling for our living/bedroom. Our kitchen will be a warm golden yellow with the same trim. Maybe our hall will be a nice golden orange (or some such).</p>

	<p>It&#8217;d be easier to get excited about doing the work if we didn&#8217;t have leaking chimneys. We&#8217;ll have to live with it for another few months. At least he&#8217;s around working on our bathroom right now. Getting the plumbing figured out will be a huge jump (water in our kitchen, no taking baths in Darlene&#8217;s glaze room).</p>



 

<p class="postmetadata alt">

<small>This entry was posted on Dec 17 by <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?author=E.G.+Yarnetsky">E.G. Yarnetsky</a>. You can skip to the end and leave a response using the comment form.</small></p>

</div>

</div>




	

